---
import ToolPage from '../../layouts/ToolPage.astro'
import YamlJsonIsland from '../../islands/YamlJsonIsland'
import { getToolMeta } from '@devkits/core'

const meta = getToolMeta('yaml-json')!
---

<ToolPage meta={meta}>
  <YamlJsonIsland client:load />

  <section class="mt-12 max-w-3xl">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-4">How to Use</h2>
    <div class="prose prose-gray dark:prose-invert max-w-none text-sm leading-relaxed space-y-3">
      <p>
        Paste YAML into the left panel and click <strong>Convert to JSON</strong> to get a
        formatted JSON equivalent on the right, or paste JSON and click
        <strong>Convert to YAML</strong> to go the other direction. The output is pretty-printed
        and syntax-highlighted for easy reading. Use the copy button to place the result on
        your clipboard instantly.
      </p>
      <p>
        Common workflows include converting Kubernetes manifests or GitHub Actions workflows
        from YAML to JSON for programmatic processing, transforming JSON API responses into
        YAML before committing them as fixture files, and validating that a YAML configuration
        file parses without errors before deploying it to a server or CI system.
      </p>
      <p>
        Conversion runs entirely in the browser, so proprietary infrastructure configurations
        and secrets in environment-specific YAML files are never sent to a server.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10 max-w-3xl">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">What are the main differences between YAML and JSON?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          YAML uses indentation to define structure instead of braces and brackets, supports
          comments with <code>#</code>, and allows multiline strings without escaping. JSON is
          a strict subset of JavaScript syntax with no comments and is more compact. YAML is
          generally preferred for human-edited configuration files, while JSON is preferred for
          machine-generated data and API payloads.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">Can YAML files contain comments?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          Yes. Any text following a <code>#</code> character on a line is treated as a comment
          and ignored by the parser. JSON does not support comments at all, so comments are lost
          when converting YAML to JSON. This is one reason YAML is preferred for configuration
          files maintained by humans.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">Why does my YAML have unexpected types after conversion?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          YAML automatically infers types: values like <code>true</code>, <code>false</code>,
          <code>null</code>, and bare numbers are parsed as their native types rather than strings.
          If you need a value to remain a string, wrap it in quotes in the YAML source. For
          example, use <code>"true"</code> instead of <code>true</code>.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">Is YAML a superset of JSON?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          YAML 1.2 is a superset of JSON — any valid JSON document is also valid YAML 1.2. This
          means you can use a YAML parser to read JSON files, though the reverse is not true:
          YAML-specific features like comments, anchors, and multi-document streams have no JSON
          equivalent.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</ToolPage>
